            <!-- Explanation -->
            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How to use the Board Game Score Tracker</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed to replace paper score pads and generic
                score apps. It works for almost any board game, card game, or
                tabletop session that uses numeric scoring.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Choose your scoring mode</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Rounds mode</strong> – each column is a round, turn,
                  or hand (great for games like <em>Yahtzee</em>,
                  <em>Qwixx</em>, trick‑taking games, or multi‑round point
                  totals).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Categories mode</strong> – each column is a scoring
                  category (ideal for games like <em>Catan</em>,
                  <em>Wingspan</em>, <em>Terraforming Mars</em>, or
                  roll‑and‑writes with multiple scoring sections).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Add players and columns</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>+ Add player</strong> to add each player. Rename
                  them by typing directly in the name field.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use <strong>+ Add</strong> and
                  <strong>− Remove last</strong> to adjust the number of rounds
                  or categories.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Double‑click a column header to rename it (e.g., “Round 1”,
                  “Resources”, “Bonus VP”).
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>3. Enter scores and see rankings update live</h3>
              <p>Type scores into the cells. The calculator automatically:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Calculates each player’s <strong>total score</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  Sorts players by total and shows their <strong>rank</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Optionally <strong>highlights the current leader</strong> so
                  you can see who’s ahead at a glance.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Negative scores are supported, so you can track penalties,
                debts, or lost points.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Copy or save your results</h3>
              <p>
                When the game ends, click <strong>Copy summary</strong> to copy
                a plain‑text recap of the game:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Game name (if you entered one).</li>
                <li>Players, totals, and ranks.</li>
                <li>Per‑round or per‑category breakdown.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Paste this into a BoardGameGeek session log, a spreadsheet, a
                group chat, or your own gaming journal.
              </p>

              <h2>Behind the scenes: how scores and ranks are calculated</h2>
              <p>
                For each player, the total score is the sum of all numeric
                entries across the row:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Total score</strong> for player <em>i</em>:</p>
                <p>\[ \text{Total}_i = \sum_{j=1}^{N} s_{ij} \]</p>
                <p>
                  where \(s_{ij}\) is the score for player <em>i</em> in round
                  or category <em>j</em>, and \(N\) is the number of columns.
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Players are then ranked by total score (highest first). If two
                or more players have the same total, they share the same rank
                and are shown as a tie. You can then apply your game’s specific
                tie‑break rules (for example, most coins, most remaining
                resources, or fewest turns).
              </p>

              <h2>Tips for using this at the table</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use landscape mode</strong> on phones or tablets for
                  more visible columns.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Designate a scorekeeper</strong> so one person manages
                  the device while others call out scores.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Rename columns</strong> to match the exact wording in
                  your game’s score pad to avoid confusion.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Copy the summary</strong> right after the game so you
                  don’t lose your results.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Privacy and data</h2>
              <p>
                All calculations run in your browser. We don’t store your
                players, scores, or game names on our servers. If you refresh or
                close the page, your current table will be cleared, so be sure
                to copy the summary if you want to keep a record.
              </p>
            </section>

